racy in society. Moreover, the inclusion or exclusion of religion following statehood may facilitate a certain type of path-dependent political culture, one with long-term political consequences. Aviad Rubin's refreshing analytical approach comparing and contrasting the region's only two longstanding democratic entities and the dynamics of religion and the state in two different religions, Islam and Judaism, facilitates generalizable lessons for emergent political regimes in the post–Arab Spring Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aDemocracyzIsraelxHistory. 0aDemocracyzTurkeyxHistory. 0aIslam and statezTurkeyxHistory. 0aJudaism and statezIsraelxHistory. 0aReligion and statezIsraelxHistory. 0aReligion and statezTurkeyxHistory. 0aReligion and state-Turkey-History. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Comparative Politics. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion and Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848078740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480787/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles